<body>
  <div class="container">
    <h1>Car Pistons Guide</h1>

    <!-- Purpose Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Purpose</h2>
      <p>The pistons are a critical component of the engine, responsible for converting the energy from fuel combustion into mechanical motion. They move up and down within the cylinders, driving the crankshaft and powering the vehicle.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Types of Pistons Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Types of Pistons</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Cast Pistons:</strong> Made by pouring molten metal into a mold. Durable and cost-effective, commonly used in standard engines.</li>
        <li><strong>Forged Pistons:</strong> Made by compressing metal under high pressure. Stronger and lighter, ideal for high-performance engines.</li>
        <li><strong>Hypereutectic Pistons:</strong> Made from a special aluminum alloy with high silicon content. Offers a balance of strength and thermal efficiency.</li>
        <li><strong>Domed Pistons:</strong> Feature a raised dome to increase compression ratio, used in high-performance engines.</li>
        <li><strong>Flat-Top Pistons:</strong> Have a flat surface, commonly used in engines with moderate compression ratios.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Components Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Components</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Piston Head:</strong> The top part of the piston that is exposed to combustion gases.</li>
        <li><strong>Piston Rings:</strong> Seal the combustion chamber, control oil consumption, and transfer heat to the cylinder walls.</li>
        <li><strong>Piston Skirt:</strong> The lower part of the piston that guides it within the cylinder.</li>
        <li><strong>Wrist Pin (Piston Pin):</strong> Connects the piston to the connecting rod.</li>
        <li><strong>Connecting Rod:</strong> Links the piston to the crankshaft, converting linear motion into rotational motion.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Maintenance Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Maintenance</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Regularly check and replace piston rings if they show signs of wear or damage.</li>
        <li>Inspect the piston and cylinder walls for scoring, cracks, or excessive wear.</li>
        <li>Ensure proper lubrication to reduce friction and prevent piston seizure.</li>
        <li>Monitor engine performance for signs of piston issues, such as reduced power or unusual noises.</li>
        <li>Use high-quality fuel and oil to prevent carbon buildup and extend piston life.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Signs of Piston Issues Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Signs of Piston Issues</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Unusual Noises:</strong> Knocking or rattling sounds may indicate piston slap or worn piston rings.</li>
        <li><strong>Reduced Engine Power:</strong> Worn or damaged pistons can reduce engine performance.</li>
        <li><strong>Excessive Oil Consumption:</strong> Worn piston rings can cause the engine to burn oil.</li>
        <li><strong>Smoke from Exhaust:</strong> Blue smoke may indicate oil burning due to piston ring failure.</li>
        <li><strong>Poor Compression:</strong> Low compression in one or more cylinders may indicate piston or ring issues.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

